<div class="container" style="margin-top: 25px">
	<div class="p-name" style="text-align:center">
		<h3 class="project-name-label">PROJECT: </h3>
		<h3 class="project-name">VAIBHAV GUPTA</h3><br><br>
	</div>
	<hr/>
	<div class="links">
		<div class="link-image link-image-2">
			<%= link_to image_tag('misc/website.png'), 'http://www.vaibhavgupta.co.uk/', target: '_blank' %>
		</div> 
	</div><br />
	<p class="highlights">"A Portfolio Website for a Professional Video Game Designer"</p>
		<h3 class="project-deliverables" style="text-align: center; font-size: 30px; font-family: 'Raleway-Light', sans-serif">
			DELIVERABLES
		</h3><br />
		<div class="dev-project-roles">
			<div class="dev-role">PROTOTYPES</div>
			<div class="dev-role">RESPONSIVE WEBSITE</div>
			<div class="dev-role">ANALYTICS INTEGRATION</div>
		</div><br>
		<div class="jumbotron">
			<h3 class="dev-project-description-label">THE CLIENT'S REQUIREMENTS</h3>
				<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
					The client was a professional designer in the video game sector. He wanted a website to showcase all his primary design projects including a modded game, a UX project, and a comic book among others. The information for each specific project needed to be added as well.
				</p>
				<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
					I built the website with Ruby as the primary backend language and Rails as the framework. In addition to using HTML5 and CSS3 elements, I also used several jQuery plugins to make the site more dynamic and interactive.
				</p>
		</div>
		<div class="jumbotron" style="background-color: #fff">
			<h3 class="dev-project-description-label">AN INTERACTIVE LANDING PAGE</h3>
			<div class="cem-listng-row">
				<div class="cem-listing">
					<%= image_tag('vaibhavgupta/layout-1.png') %>
				</div>
				<div class="cem-listing">
					<%= image_tag('vaibhavgupta/layout-2.png') %>
				</div>
			</div><br><br>
			<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
				The landing page shows a collection of all the major projects that the designer had worked on. I didn't want to use static text as it did not resonate well with the rest of site. Instead, when a user hovers over a project image, the background becomes transparent and the project title appears.
			</p>
			<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
				I was able to achieve this with only css. The hover function was very important because it added another level of interactivity to the website.
			</p><br>
			<div class="jumbotron">
				<h3 class="dev-project-description-label">ADD THE MOST RELEVANT INFORMATION PER PROJECT</h3>
				<div class="cem-listng-row">
					<div class="cem-listing">
						<%= image_tag('vaibhavgupta/layout-3.png') %>
					</div>
					<div class="cem-listing">
						<%= image_tag('vaibhavgupta/layout-4.png') %>
					</div>
				</div><br><br>
				<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
					Every project will have a row of images relevant to that project designed with flexslider. The slider's API is modified to automatically circulate all the images (or the user can click on the arrows at both extremeties to navigate acrsoss the images)
				</p>
				<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
					Under the images, the project details are broken down by 'OBJECTIVE', 'MY ROLE', and, 'OUTCOME' to detail the process of developing each project.
				</p>
				<p class="dev-project-description" style="margin-top: 10px">
					Finally at the bottom of the page, there are two navigation links NEXT and PREVIOUS that takes the users to the next or previous projects in the portfolio.
				</p>
			</div>
	<h3 class="dev-project-description-label">BUILT WITH</h3>
